      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Pat the beef bites dry with paper towels to remove excess moisture. Season with salt, pepper, garlic powder, and smoked paprika.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "For enhanced flavor, heat olive oil in a skillet over medium-high heat. Sear the beef bites in batches, browning each side for 1-2 minutes. This step is optional but adds depth to the dish.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Toss the halved or quartered potatoes with olive oil, salt, and pepper in a large mixing bowl. This ensures they are evenly seasoned and ready to absorb the garlic butter sauce.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "In a small bowl, whisk together melted butter, minced garlic, thyme, rosemary, beef broth, and Worcestershire sauce.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Place the seasoned potatoes in the bottom of the slow cooker. Layer the seasoned beef bites on top of the potatoes. Pour the garlic butter sauce evenly over the beef and potatoes, ensuring everything is well coated.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cover the slow cooker with the lid. For low heat: Cook for 6-8 hours. For high heat: Cook for 3-4 hours.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Check the beef and potatoes for tenderness before serving. Both should be fork-tender and infused with the garlic butter flavor.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Garnish and Serve - Sprinkle chopped parsley over the dish for a pop of freshness. Optional: Add a sprinkle of grated Parmesan for extra richness. Serve warm, straight from the slow cooker, with crusty bread or a green salad on the side.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": "A few of the more common issues, and what tends to fix them.",
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Salt a pinch at a time, tasting. A squeeze of lemon or splash of vinegar at the end lifts most savoury dishes.",
              "cause": "Underseasoned or no acid.",
              "symptom": "The dish tastes flat"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pull off the heat a minute or two before you think it's done. Plate straight away, or transfer to a warmed serving dish.",
              "cause": "Carryover cooking, food keeps cooking on the hot pan after the heat goes off.",
              "symptom": "It's overcooked by the time it reaches the table"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Drop the heat and give it longer. A probe thermometer is the only reliable check for meat.",
              "cause": "Heat too high, browned the outside before the middle warmed through.",
              "symptom": "It's undercooked in the middle"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reheat covered with a splash of stock or water, on a low heat. Microwave on 60% power if using one, gentler than full blast.",
              "cause": "Reheated uncovered, or no liquid in the pan.",
              "symptom": "The leftovers were dry"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "If something goes wrong"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Variations",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Vegetarian swap: replace meat with mushrooms, lentils, or beans, adjust seasoning to compensate.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Spice version: a pinch of chilli flakes or cracked black pepper at the end shifts the dish without losing its character.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make ahead, freezing, leftovers",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Best fresh. Leftovers keep two days in the fridge; reheat covered with a splash of liquid.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A British home cook's dish. It sits among the recipes families remember without thinking about, the kind that gets adjusted across generations and never quite the same twice.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
